<h1>Set up the data how I want it</h1>

<p>Just in case, I&#39;ll duplicate <em>college</em> as a string variable, and make 
  <em>grad college</em> a factor.</p>

<pre><code class="r">data$College_char &lt;- as.character(data$College)
data$Grad_coll_fact &lt;- as.factor(data$Grad_coll)
</code></pre>

<p>Since I&#39;m dropping some colleges, I&#39;ll replicate <em>data</em> as <em>sample</em>, to signify it&#39;s the analysis sample</p>

<p><strong>DROP</strong>: Lucy Cavendish, as no wine budget, and the Grad colleges, as they aren&#39;t ranked.</p>

<pre><code class="r">sample &lt;- subset(data, College_char != &quot;Lucy Cavendish&quot;)
sample &lt;- subset(sample, Grad_coll == FALSE)
</code></pre>

<p>Now general tidying - Make college name, row name. Add the age of college and members in a college. And make a log of the wine budget.</p>

<pre><code class="r">sample &lt;- data.frame(sample[, -1], row.names = sample[, 1])
sample$Age_College &lt;- 2014 - sample$Founded
sample$Members &lt;- sample$Fellows + sample$Students
sample$log_Wine_budget &lt;- log(sample$Wine_budget)
</code></pre>

<h1>Model the data!</h1>

<h2>First by hand</h2>

<p>R has functions to make running regressions easy. But it&#39;s good to know how they work. So
 first I&#39;ll do a simple analysis by hand of \( y=\alpha+\beta_1 X_1 \).</p>

<pre><code class="r">x &lt;- sample$log_Wine_budget
y &lt;- sample$Firsts_2013
x_bar &lt;- mean(x)
y_bar &lt;- mean(y)
beta_hat_1 &lt;- sum((x - x_bar) * (y - y_bar))/sum((x - x_bar)^2)
beta_hat_0 &lt;- y_bar - beta_hat_1 * x_bar
cat(beta_hat_0, beta_hat_1)
</code></pre>

<pre><code>## -46.16 6.221
</code></pre>

<p>So here we have the intercept, and the coefficient for log of the wine budget, in that order.</p>

<h2>Now using a command</h2>

<pre><code class="r">simple &lt;- lm(Firsts_2013 ~ log_Wine_budget, data = sample)
summary(simple)
</code></pre>

<p>So why did I use the log? Below is the model with raw wine budget.</p>

<pre><code class="r">raw_fit &lt;- lm(Firsts_2013 ~ Wine_budget, data = sample)
coef(raw_fit)
</code></pre>

<pre><code>## (Intercept) Wine_budget 
## 18.32024204  0.00005192
</code></pre>

<pre><code class="r">summary(raw_fit)$r.squared
</code></pre>

<pre><code>## [1] 0.3973
</code></pre>

<p>So the r-squared suggests this doesn&#39;t fit the data as well. So without even looking at whether the assumptions behind the regression are right, it looks like log is a lot better. Usually you look at the fit by looking at the residuals, but here it&#39;s pretty easy to see in the raw data (below) that a log curve is going to be better.</p>

<h1>Cook&#39;s D</h1>

<p>We can display the observations that have relatively large values of data.
 A conventional cut-off point is 4 over n, where n is the number of observations in
 the data set. We will use this criterion to select the values to display.</p>

<pre><code class="r">d1 &lt;- cooks.distance(ols)
r &lt;- stdres(ols)
a &lt;- cbind(sample, d1, r)
a[d1 &gt; 4/nrow(sample), c(&quot;Firsts_2013&quot;, &quot;Members&quot;, &quot;Age_College&quot;, &quot;log_Wine_budget&quot;, 
    &quot;Percent_female&quot;)]
</code></pre>

## Homerton        16.0    1414          38           10.24             63
## Trinity         41.7    1245         468           12.32             37
</code></pre>

<h1>Compare two regressions in a plot</h1>

<p>Set the wine budget we want to plot over</p>

<pre><code class="r">attach(sample)  # save typing it again and again
wine_min &lt;- log(10000)
wine_max &lt;- log(400000)
wine_step &lt;- 40
plot_data &lt;- data.frame(log_Wine_budget = seq(from = wine_min, to = wine_max, 
    length.out = wine_step))
</code></pre>

<p>Simple OLS model</p>

<pre><code class="r">pred_simple &lt;- data.frame(predict(simple, plot_data, interval = &quot;predict&quot;))
</code></pre>

<p>Add in other variables needed at means</p>

<pre><code class="r">plot_data$Age_College &lt;- mean(Age_College)
plot_data$Percent_female &lt;- mean(Percent_female)
plot_data$Members &lt;- mean(Members)
</code></pre>

<p>Final OLS model </p>

<pre><code class="r">ols &lt;- lm(Firsts_2013 ~ log_Wine_budget + Age_College + Percent_female + Members, 
    data = sample)
pred_ols &lt;- data.frame(predict(ols, plot_data, interval = &quot;predict&quot;))
detach(sample)
</code></pre>

<p>Merge plots and make wine budget in a readable scale.</p>

<pre><code class="r">plot_data$pred_simple &lt;- pred_simple$fit
plot_data$pred_ols &lt;- pred_ols$fit
plot_data$Wine_budget &lt;- exp(plot_data$log_Wine_budget)
</code></pre>

<h2>Plot it</h2>
